==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pout
<hw>Pout</hw> <pr>(p⟦oomac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>poulet</ets>. See <er>Poult</er>.]</ety> <def>The young of some
birds, as grouse; a young fowl.</def> <rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pout
<hw>Pout</hw> <pr>(p⟦oomac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To shoot
pouts.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pout
<hw>Pout</hw> <pr>(pout)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pouted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pouting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>pouten</ets>, of
uncertain origin; cf. Prov. <ets>pot</ets> lip, Prov. F.
<ets>potte</ets>, faire la <ets>potte</ets> to pout, W. <ets>pwdu</ets>
to pout, be sullen, <ets>poten</ets>, <ets>potten</ets>, a paunch,
belly.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To thrust out the lips, as in sullenness
or displeasure; hence, to look sullen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>poutest</qex> upon thy fortune and thy love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To protrude.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Pouting</xex>
lips.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pout
<hw>Pout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sullen protrusion of the lips; a fit
of sullenness.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Jack's in the <xex>pouts</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>J. & H. Smith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Pout
<hw>Pout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Eelpout</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European whiting pout or bib.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Eel pout</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Eelpout</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Horn pout</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Horned pout</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Bullhead</er> <sd>(b)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

